Theia Ingestor – OTDR, Fingerprint & Alarm Handling

Context

The current Theia-ingestor runs in a loop and polls data periodically. This is not aligned with our design goal:
    •    The ingestor is intended to be a reactive system that partly works autonomously and interacts with ALM devices.
    •    Sequences of activities (commands) should be defined as reusable building blocks.
    •    These commands are exposed to the Theia-frontend, invoked via Theia-backend, and executed by Theia-ingestor through Kafka.
    •    Local persistence in SQLite is used as cache, while all significant results and events are sent upstream via Kafka.

⸻

Requirements

1. OTDR Measurement Command
    •    Source example: project/doc/1-perform-otdr.sh.
    •    Flow:
    1.    Ingestor triggers ALM to perform an OTDR scan for a given trace.
    2.    OTDR parameters (distance, length, pulse width, etc.) are set through SNMP.
    3.    Measurement is downloaded from ALM (via REST if needed).
    4.    Store result and metadata in SQLite cache.
    5.    Send measurement + metadata to Kafka.

⸻

2. Fingerprint Command
    •    Source example: project/doc/1-perform-fp.sh.
    •    Flow:
    1.    Trigger a Fingerprint operation from frontend.
    2.    Ingestor executes SNMP/REST commands to start FP measurement.
    3.    FP trace is downloaded from ALM.
    4.    Cache result in SQLite.
    5.    Send fingerprint + metadata via Kafka.

⸻

3. Alarm Collection
    •    Source example: project/doc/1-get-alarm.sh (→ ChatGPT’s get-alarms-plus.sh).
    •    Flow:
    1.    Ingestor runs a goroutine that polls ALM alarms every 60s.
    2.    Keep the alarm list updated in SQLite.
    3.    On new alarms, send event immediately to Kafka backend.
    4.    Map alarms with OID/Port to human-readable metadata.

⸻

4. Wrapper Functions for ALM Commands
    •    Source: project/doc/alm-port3-setup.md.
    •    Implement Go wrappers for:
    •    Setting port metadata (name, remark, perf monitoring enable).
    •    Configuring thresholds (loss budgets, deviation).
    •    Running measurements (OTDR, Fingerprint, Fault Analysis, Fiber Identifier).
    •    Cloning thresholds between ports.
    •    These wrappers should encapsulate SNMP calls and optionally REST calls.
    •    They should expose clean Go methods for use in reactive command flows.

⸻

Cross-functional Work
    •    Product Owner: Decide whether this work requires a new epic or can be folded into existing Kafka integration epic. Create issues for OTDR, FP, Alarms, Wrapper implementation.
    •    Architect: Propose integration pattern — update Kafka contracts if needed (currently, only polled measurements are sent). Define schemas for new Kafka events.
    •    Coder: Implement wrappers, OTDR & FP workflows, alarm polling routine. Integrate SQLite caching and Kafka publishing.
    •    Documentation Writer: Update developer docs (docs/ folder). Clean up old polling-only references. Document new commands and workflows.

⸻

Prompt for Agentic System

  Extend Theia-ingestor to support reactive ALM command execution:
  - OTDR scan (SNMP trigger + REST fetch + SQLite + Kafka)
  - Fingerprint (SNMP/REST + SQLite + Kafka)

Data Center Colocation Provider 
The Opportunity 
Modern enterprises, hyperscalers, and financial firms are increasingly relying on low-latency, high-reliability fiber cross-connects to power their mission-critical operations. From high-frequency trading and distributed AI clusters to storage replication and multi-tenant colocation services, fiber is the silent backbone behind applications where performance, uptime, and resilience are non-negotiable.
Yet despite this reliance, most fiber cross-connects in data centers and edge facilities are still sold as “dumb pipes,” unmonitored, unverified, and devoid of telemetry. These links lack embedded diagnostics, real-time signal health, or SLA-backed guarantees. When issues arise, standard Layer 2/3 monitoring tools often report “green” while users experience packet loss, jitter, or unexplained latency. The physical layer becomes an operational blind spot for both tenants and providers.
This presents a clear opportunity for transformation. As customers demand greater visibility, accountability, and operational assurance, the pressure grows on data centers and network providers to deliver intelligent, service-aware interconnects that align with modern SLA and BCDR expectations.
Theia bridges this gap. By embedding per-customer, per-fiber OTDR and passive optical monitoring into every cross-connect, Theia transforms standard fiber into a high-integrity, always-observable infrastructure layer. Faults are detected in real time, localized within meters, and visualized through GIS-based trace reports, without impacting live traffic. The system is multi-tenant, enabling secure, scoped visibility for each customer, whether they’re a hyperscaler, MSP, or enterprise with mission-critical applications.
Benefits to the Data Center Provider
The data center integrates Theia Fiber Monitoring directly and passively into its cross-connect fabric, turning every fiber pair into a monitored integrated OTDR service. 
Each cross-connect includes:
•    Initial OTDR fingerprinting upon turn-up
•    Passive, real-time signal monitoring with automatic degradation alerts
•    On-demand OTDR diagnostics to isolate faults or anomalies
•    GIS-based visual maps of fiber routes and fault locations
•    Custom SLA-tiered plans with response time commitments
By integrating Theia’s passive optical monitoring into their fiber cross-connect infrastructure, data center providers significantly elevate their ability to deliver high-integrity, SLA-capable connectivity. Theia provides real-time, non-intrusive visibility into the physical health of every fiber, with multi-tenancy support down to the single customer, single fiber level. This allows operators to offer each tenant their own dedicated, fully virtualized OTDR system as part of their cross-connect, transforming a simple patch into an intelligent, actively monitored service.
For customers running latency-sensitive or mission-critical workloads, such as those in finance, AI, or media, this per-fiber visibility provides confidence that their interconnects are continuously verified and protected. Theia detects subtle degradations, such as dirty connectors, microbends, or passive optical loss issues that typically fall below traditional Layer 2/3 alarms but can still disrupt real-time performance. These are flagged through passive monitoring without impacting live traffic.
Operationally, Theia automates the diagnostic workflow. When anomalies are observed, the platform initiates an on-demand OTDR scan and pinpoints the degradation to a specific splice, connector, or segment. The issue is mapped on a GIS overlay and documented with a timestamped trace, enabling technicians to resolve problems without guesswork. Because Theia is fully multi-tenant, all diagnostics, reports, and alerts are isolated per customer per fiber link, allowing support teams to quickly and securely triage issues without cross-tenant exposure.
Theia also supports SLA enforcement and tenant accountability. Historical trace data, event logs, and localized fault evidence allow data center operators to demonstrate fiber health, prove resolution timelines, and maintain transparency with customers. This strengthens relationships with high-value tenants and enables the facility to stand behind its cross-connect SLAs with measurable proof.
With Theia, cross-connects become more than physical links; they become visible, verifiable, and supportable fiber services that elevate the standard for interconnect assurance across the facility.



Use Case 1
Financial: Direct cross-connects between collocated infrastructure in a Tier 2 facility
Scenario 
A critical application begins to underperform, with users reporting noticeable slowdowns and application-perceived latency. Further investigation reveals a measurable increase in latency over a high-speed optical link that supports the workload.
Despite the performance degradation, traditional monitoring systems, including Layer 2/3 tools, SNMP polling, and interface health checks, report no errors or alarms.
From a network perspective, everything appears fully operational, making root cause identification difficult and delaying resolution.
The Cause
The performance issue stemmed from a subtle physical degradation along the optical path, most likely due to fiber stress, a slightly damaged connector, or unintended passive interference introduced during handling or re-routing.
This degradation resulted in incremental optical loss, but not at a level high enough to trigger alarms from transceivers or standard monitoring tools. From a power and protocol perspective, the link appeared to be functioning normally.
However, even small deviations in signal quality can significantly impact latency-sensitive or high throughput applications, particularly in financial services, cloud interconnects, or real-time workloads.
Because traditional tools do not inspect the physical layer in real-time, the issue remained undetected and unaddressed, although not severe enough to trigger transceiver alarms, yet sufficient to impact real-time performance.
How Theia Assists
Theia continuously monitors optical signal integrity through passive scans, allowing it to detect early signs of physical degradation even before alarms are triggered.
Upon identifying an anomaly, Theia automatically performs a targeted OTDR measurement to pinpoint the issue with meter-level accuracy.
It then generates a clear, time-stamped trace report and maps the exact fault location using GIS.
This actionable insight enables local teams to quickly triage issues and allows them to escalate the problem directly to the carrier with precise location data, thereby accelerating resolution and eliminating the guesswork typically involved in fiber troubleshooting.



Use Case 2
Regional Internet Service Provider (ISP) – Metro Fiber Network
Scenario 
A major enterprise customer starts reporting intermittent packet loss on a 10G DIA circuit delivered over the ISP’s metro ring.
The issue is sporadic, with no alarms on the DWDM equipment, no dropped links, and power levels within specification. NOC engineers can’t reproduce the problem on demand.
Support escalations pile up. Field techs waste time swapping optics and rerouting traffic without results.
The Cause
The issue was caused by a subtle degradation in the physical fiber path commonly referred to as a "dirty fiber" condition. While not severe enough to trigger alarms or link failures, the impairment disrupted real-time traffic by destabilizing signal quality, leading to packet loss, jitter, and application-level performance issues.
Because this type of degradation occurs below traditional monitoring thresholds, it remained invisible to standard tools, prolonging diagnosis and increasing customer impact.
How Theia Assists 
Theia continuously monitors optical signal integrity using passive, non-intrusive scans without disrupting live traffic.
In this case, it would detect subtle irregularities in insertion loss and signal stability that would have gone unnoticed by traditional tools. Theia then automatically triggers an on-demand OTDR scan, precisely localizing the degradation to a splice point along the mid-mile segment.
A timestamped trace report and GIS-based location overlay were instantly generated, enabling the field team to respond with exact fault coordinates, eliminating guesswork, unnecessary testing, and wasted truck rolls.

 
Use Case 3
NOC Support: Proving Fiber Integrity Remotely to Avoid Unnecessary Truck Rolls
Scenario:
A business customer contacts their ISP’s NOC, reporting frequent application timeouts and believes the issue lies in their fiber connection. They demand an immediate investigation, suspecting a damaged cable or a poor splice. Traditionally, the ISP might dispatch a field technician with an OTDR to validate the link, a time-consuming and costly process that often reveals no fault at all.
The customer’s perception of a "bad fiber" isn’t backed by any alarms on the network side. Power levels are within an acceptable range, SNMP shows clean interfaces, and routers report no errors. However, without real-time physical layer visibility, the ISP has no way to verify that the fiber is clean without physically visiting the field, risking wasted truck rolls, technician time, and SLA issues.
The Cause
In this case, the fiber infrastructure was fully intact. The issue stemmed from upstream equipment or application-layer instability, such as a misconfigured firewall, an oversubscribed WAN port, or a congested overlay network. However, without physical-layer insight, the customer assumed the fiber itself was the culprit.
Because the degradation wasn’t real, traditional monitoring tools showed no anomalies, but the absence of fiber-level proof would have typically led to unnecessary dispatches and troubleshooting in the field.
How Theia Assists 
With Theia installed, the NOC immediately reviews current and historical passive signal scans on the customer’s assigned fiber. No reflectance spikes, loss trends, or instability are detected. To ensure thoroughness, the system performs an on-demand OTDR scan in seconds, while the link remains live.
The scan confirms a clean fiber path end-to-end, with no measurable faults, bends, or splice loss. A timestamped OTDR trace and GIS-verified link integrity report is attached to the customer’s ticket as proof.
The NOC contacts the customer with definitive, layer-1 verified assurance:
“Your fiber connection is performing within specification. We recommend further troubleshooting upstream (CPE, switch, application). A field dispatch is not required.”
 
Use Case 4
Utility: SLA Assurance for Fiber Backhaul
Scenario
A regional utility operates a multi-site fiber backbone connecting substations, control centers, and remote monitoring equipment as part of its SCADA and smart grid infrastructure. Some fiber spans are owned; others are leased from regional providers. These links are mission-critical, supporting grid telemetry, load balancing, voltage regulation, and outage restoration.
Because performance impacts in the physical layer can lead to data loss or control delays, the utility requires continuous visibility into fiber health to ensure compliance with NERC reliability standards and internal SLA thresholds. Traditional monitoring tools only cover Layers 2 and 3, leaving the optical layer unmonitored.
The Cause
Minor physical degradations such as weather-induced stress, connector contamination at field enclosures, or intermittent reflections from aging splices can occur anywhere along the route. These issues may not cause immediate outages but still undermine signal quality, create silent data corruption, or introduce delays in command-and-control traffic between grid assets.
On leased spans, the utility lacks direct fiber-level visibility, which makes it challenging to diagnose issues, validate SLA compliance, or determine whether to dispatch a field crew or escalate the issue to the provider.
How Theia Assists
Theia continuously monitors each fiber segment using non-intrusive passive signal analysis, establishing a real-time health baseline and trend history. If signal stability, loss patterns, or reflection characteristics deviate from the fingerprint, Theia flags the anomaly.
The system then automatically triggers an OTDR scan on the affected segment, even across leased links, and precisely localizes the degradation to a splice point or cabinet. The resulting trace, timestamped and GIS-mapped, enables the utility to take targeted action: escalate the issue with proof to the fiber provider or dispatch a crew with exact fault coordinates.
Over time, Theia provides auditable fiber integrity logs that help ensure SLA conformance, support regulatory documentation, and minimize downtime from unnecessary truck rolls.
 
Use Case 5
Government or Defense contractor Fiber Tap Detection & Security Assurance
Government agencies, defense contractors, or privacy-sensitive enterprises rely on leased dark fiber to connect remote offices, data centers, or secure facilities. These circuits handle classified or sensitive data, and while they are physically secured at endpoints, the fiber itself traverses third-party infrastructure, often with no visibility into what's happening between A and B.
Because physical-layer access can be exploited to install passive optical taps or splitters, ensuring the fiber has not been compromised is critical. Traditional network security tools provide no protection at the physical layer, leaving a blind spot that attackers could exploit to siphon traffic silently.
Fiber tapping, whether malicious or accidental, introduces reflectance or insertion loss events into the optical path. These may not cause an outage or alarm and would not trigger alerts on routers or switches. Yet even a subtle change in signal characteristics can indicate that a splitter or unauthorized connection has been introduced, putting secure communications at risk.
How Theia Assists
Theia provides continuous passive signal monitoring to establish a baseline optical fingerprint of each fiber link. This includes reflectance levels, insertion loss, and signal stability metrics. Any deviation, such as a new reflective point or a slight loss or increase, triggers an alert.
Upon detection, Theia automatically performs a targeted OTDR scan, identifying the precise location of the anomaly to within a few meters. The result is a timestamped trace and GIS-mapped report showing exactly where and when a potential tap or splice was introduced.
This allows security teams to:
•    Investigate with physical verification
•    Alert the fiber provider or law enforcement
•    Prove chain-of-custody integrity for leased circuits
•    Fulfill compliance mandates for secure optical transport
With Theia, organizations gain real-time, per-fiber intrusion detection without interrupting live traffic or relying on third-party monitoring. This level of physical-layer assurance is essential for networks where data confidentiality is non-negotiable.

Defend Your Network at the Physical Layer
Fiber optic networks carry the world’s most critical data but they are often blind to physical threats. While most monitoring focuses on uptime and bandwidth, fiber tapping bypasses traditional tools entirely by intercepting light at the source. Theia provides real-time detection of physical intrusions across your dark fiber infrastructure, giving you full visibility into what’s happening in the field.
What is a Fiber Tap?
A fiber tap is a physical interception of optical light, typically using a microbend, coupler, or splice, that allows someone to access data flowing through a fiber optic cable. Because the light signal continues uninterrupted, traditional monitoring and NOC tools never detect the breach. These taps can include:
•    Passive bends or microbend taps
•    In-line optical splitters inserted during maintenance
•    Reflection-based taps that siphon optical power
•    Unauthorized splices with hidden tail fibers
•    Even temporary or accidental access can lead to serious operational risk and service degradation.
How Theia Detects Taps
Theia deploys inline OTDR (Optical Time-Domain Reflectometer) sensors that continuously scan fiber spans and report back to our cloud-based platform. By establishing a baseline signal profile for each span, Theia detects changes in reflectance, loss, and unexpected reflections that may signal the presence of a tap or other abnormal condition.
Anomaly detection engines track deviations and surface them within seconds, helping teams respond faster than ever.
Detecting Unauthorized Physical Handling
Not every incident is a full tap or cut. Sometimes, the risk begins with subtle, unauthorized handling—such as someone bending or touching fiber when they shouldn’t.
Theia detects:
•    Movement or reconnection of patch cords
•    Unscheduled splice tray access
•    Fiber slack being bent, pressed, or relocated
•    Unapproved test equipment is being connected
•    Physical contact during nearby construction
These events create optical fingerprints—such as minor backscatter changes or reflections—that Theia recognizes instantly. This provides visibility into physical-layer events that are typically unreported or unnoticed.
